# 12. 幸せになる音楽を

Young Kanade: (Dad's been shut up in his room a lot lately.)
Young Kanade: (I wonder if he's just busy with work. He's always up working on his songs until late. He seems a bit down, too.)
Young Kanade: (Oh, I have an idea. Maybe I'll try writing a song for him.)
Young Kanade: (He was always happy when I did it before. Maybe it'll help cheer him up.)
Kanade's Father: I'm home, Kanade.
Young Kanade: Oh, hi Dad. Isn't it rare for you to leave the house for work?
Kanade's Father: Oh, I managed to win that competition today.
Young Kanade: What? Really?!
Kanade's Father: Yeah. They particularly liked the bit you added, Kanade. They said they're going to use that part in a commercial.
Kanade's Father: It's all thanks to you, Kanade. Thank you. I should be able to get some more work after this.
Young Kanade: That's great, Dad! Oh, I should have made a special dinner or something!
Young Kanade: I'll go buy something to cook. What sounds good to... Hm?
Kanade's Father: ...
Young Kanade: Dad, you look a little pale. Are you feeling okay?
Kanade's Father: No, I'm just a bit tired from lack of sleep. I'm sure I'll be fine if I lie down for a while.
Young Kanade: Are you sure? If you say so...
Kanade's Father: And I'm saying it's not possible!
Young Kanade: Wh-What's wrong, Dad? What are you yelling for?
Kanade's Father: Oh, it's okay, Kanade. It's nothing. I'm just on the phone about work.
Voice On Phone: We're not trying to be unreasonable. We'd just like something a little more like the song in the commercial.
Kanade's Father: Kanade, go back to your room.
Young Kanade: O-Okay...
Kanade's Father: No, this arrangement won't cut it.
Kanade's Father: They'll never accept it like this. It needs something new. Something more modern.
Young Kanade: Dad, I made some dinner.
Kanade's Father: No, this isn't right.
Kanade's Father: It's done! I finally did it!
Kanade's Father: They can't call THIS old fashioned. It's probably even better than...
Young Kanade: Dad, do you have a minute?
Kanade's Father: Hm? Oh, of course. What is it, Kanade?
Young Kanade: You've seemed really down lately, so I thought I'd make you a song.
Kanade's Father: You what?
Young Kanade: I, uh...was hoping you could listen to it.
Kanade's Father: S-Sure...
Kanade's Father: !!
Kanade's Father: Did you really make this all by yourself?
Young Kanade: Yeah. I only worked on it a little while I was taking breaks from studying, though, so it's not that good.
Kanade's Father: .....
Kanade's Father: You really are amazing, Kanade.
Kanade's Father: You have such a gift, Kanade. You've really been blessed by music.
Young Kanade: Huh? I don't know about that... Hehe. Are you feeling a little better?
Kanade's Father: ..... ...Yes, I am.
Kanade's Father: Kanade.
Young Kanade: Hm?
Kanade's Father: Kanade, make sure you keep creating your own music.
Kanade's Father: I'm sure there will be many people who enjoy listening to your music. They're going to need you.
Young Kanade: Dad?
Young Kanade: Dad, it's morning. If you don't wake up soon... Huh?
Young Kanade: Dad!
Doctor: Your father seems to be suffering from overwork. It's affecting his ability to remember things.
Doctor: Thankfully, there's no danger to his mind or body. This sort of thing is a result of psychological stress. With a little rest, most people recover within a few days, but...
Young Kanade: There are people who don't recover?
Doctor: I'm afraid so. They're still able to function day to day, however they have difficulty remembering things properly.
Young Kanade: .....
Young Kanade: What am I supposed to do now?
Young Kanade: Dad...
Young Kanade: Hm? Is this Dad's diary?
Young Kanade: .....
Father's Diary: “7th - I responded to the client's claim that my music sounded too old-fashioned. Still, I can't keep clinging to the same old style forever.”
Young Kanade: It looks like he was using it for notes about work.
Father's Diary: “23rd - I'm finally getting used to working with the computer, but I'm still far from mastering all the different functions. I still have a lot to learn.”
Father's Diary: “14th - Kanade helped with the arrangement I was having trouble with. To be honest, I was really surprised. She might have a gift for this.”
Father's Diary: “30th - I won the competition, but I'm finding it hard to celebrate.”
Young Kanade: Huh? Why?
Father's Diary: “The only part they really liked was the section Kanade made. That's her music, not mine.”
Father's Diary: “22nd - I've been getting more work since the commercial started airing, but the clients all want something similar to it. I keep telling them I can't, but they insist.”
Young Kanade: Oh...
Kanade's Father: And I'm saying it's not possible!
Father's Diary: “They all laugh at how old-fashioned my music sounds, despite the commercial piece being so well polished. What am I missing?”
Father's Diary: “8th - Kanade gave me a song she made.”
Young Kanade: O-Oh...
Father's Diary: “I finally realized what my music is missing. Why everyone says it sounds so outdated.”
Father's Diary: “The music I'm making is all just a cheap imitation of songs I've heard in the past.”
Father's Diary: “But Kanade's is different. Her music has the ability to touch the hearts of the people of today.”
Father's Diary: “It's all feeling instead of logic. That isn't something I can imitate.”
Father's Diary: “And yet I have to keep writing music. I need to make a living so I can take care of Kanade.”
Father's Diary: “But is that really the kind of music I want to write? The kind that can make people happy?”
Father's Diary: “I wonder if Kanade could make music like that. I may not be able to, but she might...”
Young Kanade: Dad...
Young Kanade: Have I been hurting him all this time?
Young Kanade: I... I never meant to! I was just...
Young Kanade: !!
Young Kanade: I hate this! I don't want it!
Young Kanade: If only I'd never made that stupid song!
Young Kanade: *Huff*... *Huff*...
Young Kanade: I'm sorry... Dad, I'm so sorry...
Young Kanade: .....
Young Kanade: (I just want to disappear.)
Young Kanade: (I don't even feel hungry.)
Young Kanade: (I wonder if I can just disappear if I stop eating.)
Young Kanade: Oh, Mom's music box... I must have knocked it on the floor.
Young Kanade: Dad made this song.
Young Kanade: Such a gentle melody. Mom and I both loved this song...that Dad made...
Kanade's Father: Kanade, make sure you keep creating your own music.
Young Kanade: I've got to make more.
Young Kanade: All this happened to Dad because my songs couldn't bring happiness to anyone.
Young Kanade: I have to be able to write songs that will bring happiness to others.
Young Kanade: Songs that can save anyone.
Young Kanade: I must compose... I must compose...
Young Kanade: I...mustn't ever stop composing...
